>> Does anyone know enough about the technical specifics of the FBI Wiretap
>> sections of the Digital Telephony bill to tell me whether or not they would
>> allow someone to perform a man-in-the-middle attack against a Clipper-
>> encoded conversation? Specifically, would an agent be able to add a device to
>> the phone switch that would enable him/her to route both ends of a
>conversation
>> through a 'black box' without the detection?
>>  

>   My understanding is that if the MITM had two clipper phones it would be
>no problem. Your phone talks to (echanges keys with) MITM#1, who sends the
>unencrypted voice to MITM#2, who has exchanged keys with "the party with
>whom you are speaking".

	The 3600c has an lcd screen.  Once you go into secure mode,
you are supposed to read off the number on your screen to make sure it
matches the other persons number.  No details were given on what this
number was.  I would guess its a key fingerprint.

